    "paxos": {
      "consensus_problem_addressed": "Paxos solves the consensus problem in asynchronous, fault-tolerant distributed systems where processes may fail and messages may be lost or delayed. It ensures that a single value is chosen among multiple proposed values across a set of distributed processes, even when some processes fail.",
      "leadership_handling": "Paxos is fundamentally leaderless in its basic form. It uses a phase-based approach with three roles: proposers (who propose values), acceptors (who accept and store values), and learners (who learn the chosen value). Any process can be a proposer; there is no designated leader required for correctness. However, in practice, a distinguished proposer can improve liveness and reduce message complexity.",
      "majority_quorum_requirement": "Paxos requires a strict majority (quorum) of acceptors to achieve both safety and progress. For a system with N acceptors, a quorum is any set of ⌈N/2⌉ + 1 acceptors. Safety is guaranteed because any two quorums must overlap (ensuring consistency), and progress is guaranteed when a proposer can reach a quorum and no other proposer is concurrently proposing."
    },
    "raft": {
      "consensus_problem_addressed": "Raft solves the same consensus and log replication problem as Paxos: ensuring that a distributed system of servers can agree on a sequence of commands (log entries) and apply them in the same order, tolerating server failures and network partitions.",
      "leadership_handling": "Raft is explicitly leader-based. A single leader is elected at the start of each term using randomized timeouts and voting. The leader is responsible for receiving client requests, replicating log entries to followers, and committing entries once they are replicated on a majority. If the leader fails or becomes unreachable, a new election is triggered to elect a new leader for the next term.",
      "majority_quorum_requirement": "Raft requires a strict majority (quorum) of servers for both safety and progress. For a cluster of N servers, a quorum is any set of ⌈N/2⌉ + 1 servers. A candidate must receive votes from a majority to become leader, and a leader must replicate entries to a majority of followers before committing. This ensures that any two quorums overlap, preventing split-brain scenarios and guaranteeing safety."
